spanGrp.span: ‘I saw that there was a white man with his son;
Sũã'-je-nã sige/ (_) pe sikwa kel í yaba
They were bringing fruits down in a branch.
je tsõ kalwö mĩ-wã kaljula jãrga
They put them into three baskets.
Next his son was coming on his bike and emptied one of the baskets and took it along on his bike.
Jekea yaba datse siwã/ tebeli_yaga inga je të í kõkõblö nã eta tká gugá-sã' Je mãtse-mĩ í wa í tebeli_yaga inga
At that point one can see that he took it away.
Je_jueta í juela kepi í mẽnẽtse-mĩ í wa
He was going far away alone. It was a girl.
Í damĩũ komĩ eglauña yaba rö alaglöwa
Kerwa juer ka ji/ yurö ta kepi kuna
There was no place, the place was huge and there was a lot of sunshine.
Ka kã' ta kã' blali sigenã kã'lba ebö
His feet crashed against a stone and he fell down;
Í klaskö kenã jak mẽ buganãu-mĩ
his load fell to the ground.
I deli kenã'u-mĩ inga ñala wa
It seems that three boys came out of the bush;
Í juela kepi ñerö kã'shã jãrga Yabla jeyiwa mãñã-l bi datse
they helped him to pick up the fruits.
Je të í kimẽ-gẽ (_) í kalwö jã'nã' je shtö'
They put everything back into the basket
and dusted his knee; they removed all the dust.
í këchewö pasigá-ite ĩã Kãpoi klabe wökbá-ite inga
He rode the bike again and left.
Etawage/ etaba_gicha í wagi jẽk bötsá-ka í tebeli_yaga inga í mãũ-mĩ
There it seems that the boys came back.
Jebi í juela kepi yabla bötöu-lo-te
His cap had also fallen down;
and he had left it behind; so the boys picked it up and gave it to him.
Jeska í jẽr shenã-wã siga-wa të í kwã' í da í juã' etaba_gicha
It seems that at that point his father was only starting to come down from the tree.
Juela kepi í kaga (_) jẽk jawa-gẽ ĩã jirpaña í kalklömẽ nẽ (m)
so he moved the bench back and forth.
Í të/ í kalwa inga (m)/ mẽnẽ inga je mẽnẽwe-gẽ-ite eta_eta
He probably took more and ate them.’
Banara je ki mẽnẽ í wa Je ra í yaká-pa
